>the allocation, we'd get the best of both worlds.<br /><br />Maybe slub could have separate 'struct kmem_cache' structures for each<br />slab, and not merge at that level, but then have a merged _allocator_.<br />We already have a level of indirection there due to the whole per-cpu<br />front-end, so maybe it wouldn't even cause any extra pointer chasing.<br /><br />That would allow slabtop etc to show the number of actual allocations<br />at the granularity that we want (ie you'd see who is the real user),<br />but still then use the same slab pages and avoid the slab<br />fragmentation.<br /><br />How painful would it be to try to re-organize things like this?<br />Impossible? Very hard? Or just "need to think about it a bit"?<br /><br />                                    Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
